node.text:
Grand Teton National Park has experienced many wonderful things this decade, thanks for spending the past 10 years with us! We cannot wait to see what the next decade brings.
#mygrandteton #findyourpark #encuentratuparque

node.title: Grand Teton National Park: A Look Over the Past Decade

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Grand Teton National Park on July 19, 2021. May be an image of nature.

node.text:
It's moth week! Grab your favorite lamp and settle in to learn more about the moths of Grand Teton.

Meet the cecropia moth (Hyalophora cecropia), North America's largest native moth. These moths can be found all across North America, and females have been documented with a wingspan of five to seven inches.

Cecropia moths live a short life with one central purpose: finding a mate. Their purpose is so focused that adult moths don't - and can't! - eat as they don't have a mouth. Instead, they eat so much as caterpillars that it carries them through their adult life.

Have you seen one of these gorgeous moths?

Moths are wild creatures too! If you see one while out and about, leave it be.

#MothWeek #MyGrandTeton 

NPS Photo/J. Bonney

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Grand Teton National Park on July 19, 2021. May be an image of nature.

node.text:
T. Perry/ Roy Chambers homestead on Mormon Row

Settled by Thomas Perry in 1911, this property was eventually sold to Ida Chambers in 1945 and is part of the Mormon Row homestead community.

Most American towns and cities received electricity by the early 1920s. Mormon Row wasn't supplied electricity until the late 1950s. 

Instead, the Chambers constructed their own windmill in1946 to power a generator located in the basement of their house. This windmill symbolizes the scarcity of services afforded to small, isolated communities of the early American west. It also symbolizes the true grit it took to survive and make a living on this rugged landscape. 

Photo courtesy of M.Duff

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Grand Teton National Park on July 17, 2021. May be a closeup of nature.

node.text:
How does color enhance our appreciation of the natural world?

Swipe to find out 👉

Every color in all its shades and hues can be found in nature. From the lush greens after a thunderstorm, to the subtle grays of the mountains, to the vibrancy of insects, color plays a major role in our fascination with the natural world. 

While we often think of moths as being drab and dull in color, that is certainly not always the case! The Western Sheep Moth (Hemileuca eglanterina) in Grand Teton National Park reminds us just how colorful life can be! Would we care more about moths if they were all as colorful as this species?

Fantastic colors are just one reason why we love moths; they also play an important role as pollinators and contribute to the success of ecosystems. Join us in celebrating National Moth Week!

#GrandTetonNationalPark #MyGrandTeton #FindYourPark #NationalMothWeek #NationalMothWeek2021 

Photos Courtesy of S. Textor

node.text:
Look over there, what do you see?
My binoculars make that moose look close as can be!

When viewing wildlife it's important to give them space. Stay 100yds away from bears and wolves, and 25yds away from moose, elk, bison, and other wildlife. Bringing binoculars, a spotting scope, or a camera with good zoom can help you get up-close views without actually getting close.

Animals in Grand Teton are wild and the park is their home - respect their personal space!

#PlanLikeAParkRanger #GrandPlan 

NPS Photo/J. Bonney

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Grand Teton National Park on July 16, 2021. May be an image of chipmunk and nature.

node.text:
Mmm nothing like a tasty carrot... er, earplug? 🥕🗑

Pack out what you pack in! Trash that gets left on the landscape can be picked up by ground squirrels and other animals. Wildlife doesn't always know the difference between something that's good for them and something that isn't.

Trash, snacks, and even natural foods (like carrots or apple cores) are unnatural to the landscape and potentially harmful to local wildlife. Carry out all trash and dispose it in a bear-proof trashcan at the trailhead. Never give food to wildlife - feeding animals can habituate them so they become reliant on human food sources. Habituated animals may become aggressive in their pursuit of human foods. 

Lucky for us, this little guy left the scene without making a meal out of an earplug!

#PlanLikeAParkRanger #LeaveNoTrace 

Photo courtesy of V. Steinberg

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Grand Teton National Park on July 15, 2021. May be an image of nature and mountain.

node.text:
Expectations vs reality

That's not a smudge on your glasses, that's smoke in the air! While everyone hopes for crystal-clear mountain views when visiting Grand Teton, smoke from western fires has filled the air in Jackson Hole.

To learn more about air conditions, visit fire.airnow.gov.

For local fire information, visit tetonfires.com.

#MyGrandTeton 

NPS Photos/J. Bonney

node.text:
Feeling foggy?

Take a second to calm down by watching the fog roll across Teewinot Mountain. Listen for the soothing sounds of the Ruby-crowned Kinglet, Chipping Sparrow, Yellow Warbler and the American Robin.

Where is your peaceful place?

Photo Courtesy of M.Duff

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Grand Teton National Park on July 14, 2021. May be an image of nature.

node.text:
Unlike many isolated western settlements, 27 homesteads were clustered within Mormon Row to share labor and establish a sense of community. 

Today, only about a fifth of the original structures on Mormon Row remain. However, remnants of sites like this one can be found scattered throughout the community. 

What changes have you seen in your very own community?

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Grand Teton National Park on July 13, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text.

node.text:
No new information has been reported about missing 27-year-old hiker Cian McLaughlin. The park continues to request any information the public may have that may aid in locating McLaughlin.

He was last seen in the late afternoon/early evening on Tuesday, June 8, 2021, on the south side of the Bradley/Taggart Moraine, headed south towards Taggart Lake.
An updated missing person flyer is being posted with McLaughlin’s photo and items he was last known to be carrying.

Anyone with information regarding McLaughlin’s whereabouts is urged to contact the National Park Service Investigative Services Branch:
☎️ Call or text the tip line: 888-653-0009
🌎 Online: www.nps.gov/ISB and click “Submit a Tip”
📧 Email: nps_isb@nps.gov

For the latest update (June 23) and historic media releases, please visit: https://go.nps.gov/1cah3o

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Grand Teton National Park on July 12, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and outdoors.

node.text:
Few things say summer camping like ooey, gooey, sticky marshmallows!

While marshmallows might be a campfire staple, the best ones are roasted on a small, safe fire. Grand Teton National Park, Bridger-Teton National Forest, and the National Elk Refuge are currently in stage 1 fire restrictions, meaning lighting, building, maintaining, attending or using a fire, campfire, barbecue or grill is allowed only at designated recreation sites such as established campgrounds or picnic areas. 

Help us stay #TetonSafe by keeping your fire small and making sure it's completely put out before leaving. Check current fire information at tetonfires.com.

Do you prefer your marshmallows out of the bag, golden brown, or flame-roasted?

Photos courtesy of J. Bonney

I can feel it coming in the air tonight... -Phil Collins

What's that in the air? It's smoke!

Fires across the West have blown smoke into Jackson Hole, giving the air a hazy appearance. To learn more about air conditions, visit fire.airnow.gov.

For local fire information, visit tetonfires.com.

#PlanLikeAParkRanger 

NPS Photo/J. Bonney
